flowchart_nodes.name: Ec2 Instance Connect
flowchart_nodes.purpose:
What is it?
EC2 Instance Connect is an AWS feature that lets you securely connect to an Amazon EC2 instance using temporary SSH keys instead of long-lived ones.

Why is it?
It exists to make SSH access more secure and easier to manage, reducing risks from leaked or unmanaged SSH keys and simplifying access control with AWS IAM.

When did it matter?
It became important as cloud usage scaled (late 2010s), when teams needed short-lived, auditable, IAM-based access rather than manual key distribution.

What did it influence?
It pushed cloud security toward ephemeral credentials, tighter IAM integration, better auditability, and safer DevOps workflows for managing cloud servers.

flowchart_nodes.name: SSH
flowchart_nodes.purpose:
SSH (Secure Shell) is a secure protocol used to remotely access and manage another computer over an encrypted connection. 

SSH exists to securely log into and control remote computers, protecting passwords and data from being intercepted.

It shaped modern system administration, cloud computing, DevOps, and secure automationbasically how servers are safely managed today.

All three OS it supports.
